A company is a legal entity established in accordance with the provisions of the Law based on a memorandum of association or articles of association whereby two or more persons undertake to each contribute to a profit-oriented project by providing a share of money or labor or both to share the profit or loss arising from this project. Except for this, a company may be established by the unilateral will of one person, and non-profit companies may be established in accordance with Section (7) of the Law.
A company established in accordance with the provisions of the Law shall be considered Saudi nationality, and its headquarters must be located in the Kingdom.
A company established in accordance with the provisions of the Law shall take one of the following forms
- a- The solidarity company. b- The simple recommendation company. c- The joint stock company. d- The simplified joint stock company. e- The limited liability company.
Each company shall have a commercial name in Arabic or another language, and the name may be derived from its purpose, or a distinctive name, or the name of one or more of its current or former partners or shareholders, or both, provided that it does not violate the Trade Names Law and other laws and regulations in force in the Kingdom.
The consent of the partner or shareholder, or his heirs if he died without consent, must be obtained in the case where the trade name includes any of the names of the former partners or shareholders of the company.
The trade name must be accompanied by an indication of the form of the company.
The company's trade name may be amended in accordance with the conditions prescribed for amending the company's memorandum of association or articles of association, and the amendment shall not prejudice the company's rights or obligations or the statutory measures taken or taken against it prior to the amendment.
Anyone who actively participates in the establishment of the company and contributes to its capital with a share in cash or in kind is considered a founder.
The founders submit an application for the establishment of the company and submit it to the Commercial Registry, accompanied by the memorandum of association or articles of association and the necessary data and documents according to the form of the company.
The Commercial Registry shall decide on the application that fulfills the necessary data and documents in accordance with the provisions of the Law.
If the application is rejected, it must be reasoned, and the founders have the right to appeal to the Ministry within sixty days from the date of notification of the rejection of the application.
If the grievance is rejected or if it is not resolved within (30) days from the date of submission, the founders have the right to appeal to the competent judicial authority.
Every company established in accordance with the provisions of the Law shall have a memorandum of association, except for the joint stock company, the simplified joint stock company and the limited liability company owned by one person, each of which shall have a memorandum of association.
The company's memorandum of association or articles of association must include the terms, conditions and data required by law and in accordance with the company's form.
The company's memorandum of association or articles of association must be in Arabic and may be accompanied by a translation into another language.
The Ministry prepares indicative models for the company's articles of incorporation and bylaws in accordance with the company's form.
The company's memorandum of association or articles of association, and any amendment thereto, must be in writing, otherwise the memorandum, articles of association or amendment shall be invalid, and the company's incorporation or amendment of its memorandum of association or articles of association shall be after fulfilling the necessary requirements as stipulated in the law and regulations.
The founders, partners, directors or board members, as the case may be, must register the company's memorandum of association or articles of association and any amendments thereto with the Commercial Registry, and the Commercial Registry shall publish the necessary data or documents in accordance with the provisions of the law and regulations.
Those who caused the failure to register the documents with the Commercial Registry shall be jointly liable for compensation for the damage caused to the company, partners, shareholders or third parties as a result of the failure to register.
Third parties shall have access to the data and documents stipulated in paragraph (2) of this Article, and the data and documents extracted from the Commercial Register shall be considered evidence in the face of the company and third parties.
The Memorandum of Association or Articles of Association of the Company or any amendment thereof may not be invoked against third parties until after registration with the Commercial Registry, and if one or more statements are registered, they alone shall be ineffective against third parties.
The company acquires legal personality after it is registered with the Commercial Registry, however, during the period of incorporation, the company shall have legal personality to the extent necessary for its establishment, provided that the incorporation process is completed.
The registration of the company with the Commercial Registry entails the transfer of all contracts and works carried out by the founders for its account to its liability, and the company is charged with all the expenses they spent in order to establish the company.
If the procedures for establishing a company are not fulfilled as specified in the Law, the persons who dealt or acted in the name of the company or on its account shall be personally liable in all their assets and jointly against third parties for the acts and deeds issued by them during the period of incorporation.
The company shall carry out its purposes after it is registered with the Commercial Registry and obtains the necessary licenses from the relevant competent authorities.
The founders, partners or shareholders, whether during or after the company's incorporation period, may
Conclude one or more agreements regulating the relationship between them or the company, including how their heirs can enter the company, whether in person or through a company they establish for this purpose.
A family charter that includes the organization of family ownership in the company, its governance, employment policy for family members, distribution of profits, disposal of shares or shares, dispute resolution mechanism, etc.
The family agreement or charter is binding and may be part of the company's memorandum of association or articles of association.
 It must not contravene the law or the company's memorandum and articles of association.
Contracts, abstracts and other documents issued by the company must be marked with the following statements:
a. The company's name, form, head office address, email address, if any, and registration number with the Commercial Registry.
B- The company's capital and the amount paid out of it.
This excludes the solidarity company and the simple recommendation company.
c. The phrase "under liquidation" is added to the name of the company during the liquidation period.
A partner or shareholder's share may be in cash or in kind, or both.
With the exception of joint stock and simplified joint stock companies, a partner's share may be a business in exchange for a percentage of the profits, the amount of which is specified in the company's articles of incorporation, and his share may not be his reputation or influence.
Only cash and in-kind shares shall be the capital of the company.
The founders, partners or shareholders may offer shares or shares in the company's capital to a person in exchange for performing work or services that benefit the company and achieve its objectives, without prejudice to the provisions of the Law.
If the partner or shareholder's share is a property right, a benefit right or any other right in kind, he shall be responsible - in accordance with the provisions of the sales contract - for guaranteeing the share in the event of loss, exposure, maturity or the appearance of a defect or deficiency in the share, and if his share is merely the utilization of a personal right over the property, the provisions of the lease contract shall apply, unless otherwise agreed upon.
If the partner's share is a business, he must perform the work he undertook, and any profit resulting from this work shall be the right of the company, and he may not engage in this work for his own account.
However, he shall not be obligated to provide the Company with the rights to the intellectual property resulting from such work, unless otherwise agreed.
Each partner is indebted to the company for the share they have pledged.
If the partner fails to provide his share in the company's capital within the prescribed time limit, the company may demand that he fulfill what he has pledged to it, or suspend the enforcement of the rights related to his shares, such as the right to receive profits or the right to vote in the General Assembly or on the partners' decisions, with the company reserving in all cases the right to demand compensation for the damage resulting from this.
The company's fiscal year shall be (twelve) months as specified in its Memorandum of Association or Articles of Association.
However, the fiscal year may be defined as not less than six months and not more than eighteen months starting from the date of the company's registration with the Commercial Register.
The company shall keep accounting records and supporting documents to explain its business, contracts and financial statements at the company's head office or at any other place specified by the company's director or board of directors.
Financial statements must be prepared for the company at the end of each fiscal year in accordance with the accounting standards adopted in the Kingdom, and these statements must be deposited as specified in the regulations within six months after the end of the fiscal year, in accordance with the provisions of the law.
If the preparation of the initial or annual financial statements requires the controlling company or the company that owns shares or shares in the capital of another company to obtain information from the controlling company or the company that owns shares or shares in its capital, it must provide such information to the extent that enables the controlling company or the owning company to prepare its financial statements in accordance with the accounting standards adopted in the Kingdom.
The Authority shall establish regulations for the submission of the information referred to in paragraph (3) of this Article by listed shareholding companies on the Capital Market.
The Company shall have an auditor (or more) from the auditors licensed in the Kingdom, who shall be appointed by the Company and shall determine his fees, the duration of his work and the scope of the partners, the General Assembly or the shareholders, as the case may be, and may be reappointed.
The regulations specify the maximum tenure of an individual auditor or a firm and its partner overseeing the audit.
The partners, the General Assembly or the shareholders, as the case may be, may dismiss the auditor, without prejudice to his right to compensation for the damage caused to him, if he has the right to do so.
The director or chairman of the board of directors must inform the competent authority of the removal decision and the reasons for it, within a period not exceeding five (5) days from the date of issuance of the decision.
The Auditor may retire from his assignment by written notification to the Company, and his assignment shall terminate from the date of his submission or at a later date specified in the notification, without prejudice to the right of the Company to compensate for the damage caused to it if it is warranted.
The retiring auditor is obligated to submit to the company and the competent authority - upon submission of the notification - a statement of the reasons for his retirement, and the company's director or board of directors must invite the partners or shareholders to the meeting or the general assembly, as the case may be, to consider the reasons for retirement and appoint another auditor.
The provision regarding the mandatory appointment of an auditor in Article 18 of the Law shall not apply to micro and small companies, except for the following micro and small companies
whose articles of incorporation or bylaws so stipulate.
listed on the stock market.
that issue debt instruments, current financing instruments, preferred shares, or redeemable shares.
Where the appointment of an auditor is required in accordance with the relevant regulations.
Foreign.
that owns another company or is a subsidiary of another company, unless the description of a micro or small company applies to all of them.
For the purposes of applying this paragraph, the regulations specify the criteria by which a company is characterized as a micro or small company.
In order for the provision in paragraph (1) of this Article to apply, the company must be characterized as a micro or small company during the first fiscal year of its registration with the Commercial Registry, or during two consecutive fiscal years.
One or more partners or shareholders of the company to which the provisions of paragraph (1) of this Article apply, who own at least ten percent of its shares or shares with voting rights, may request, in writing, that the company appoint an auditor in accordance with the rules specified in the regulations.
The provision relating to the mandatory appointment of an auditor contained in Article (18) of the Law shall not apply to a solidarity company except in one of the following cases
If all partners are legal persons in any form of company other than a solidarity company.
If all the partners are legal persons taking the form of a solidarity company and the partners are legal persons taking any form of company other than a solidarity company.
If the company's articles of incorporation stipulate his appointment.
The company's auditor must be independent as determined by the professional standards adopted in the Kingdom.
The auditor's work may not be combined with participation in the establishment, management, or membership of the board of directors of the company he is auditing. The auditor may not be a partner, employee, or relative of any of the company's founders, directors, or board members, nor may he buy or sell shares or stocks in the company he is auditing during the audit period.
The company's auditor shall not perform technical, administrative or consultancy work in or for the benefit of the company whose accounts he is auditing, except as specified by the regulations.
The auditor may, at any time, review the company's documents, accounting records and supporting documents, and may request the data and clarifications he deems necessary to verify the company's assets and liabilities, and other matters within the scope of his work.
The company's director or board of directors must enable him to fulfill his duty.
If the auditor encounters difficulty in this regard, he shall report this in a report to the company's director or board of directors.
If the director or the board of directors does not facilitate the work of the auditor, he shall request them to invite the partners or shareholders to the meeting or the general assembly, as the case may be, to consider the matter.
The auditor may extend this invitation if the Director or the Board of Directors fails to do so within thirty days from the date of the auditor's request.
The auditor shall submit to the partners, the General Assembly at its annual meeting, or the shareholders, a report on the company's financial statements prepared in accordance with the auditing standards adopted in the Kingdom, including the position of the company's management in enabling him to obtain the data and explanations he requested, any violations of the provisions of the Law, the company's memorandum of association or its articles of association within his jurisdiction, and his opinion on the fairness of the financial statements of the company.
The auditor must read his report or review a summary of it at the Annual General Meeting, or the report must be presented and passed, as the case may be, in accordance with the provisions of the Law.
The auditor may not disclose to the partners or shareholders at a meeting other than the General Assembly or to third parties any of the company's secrets that he has uncovered due to the performance of his work, otherwise he may be required to pay compensation in addition to the right to dismiss him.
The auditor shall be liable for the contents of his report and for any damage caused to the company, partners, shareholders or third parties due to errors committed by him in the performance of his work, and if the company has more than one auditor, they shall be jointly liable, except for those who prove that they did not participate in the error causing liability.
Partners and shareholders have the right to control the company's accounts in accordance with the provisions stipulated in the law and the company's memorandum of association or articles of association.
Annual or interim dividends may be distributed from the distributable profits to the partners or shareholders of joint stock, simplified joint stock, and limited liability companies.
If profits are distributed to partners or shareholders in violation of paragraph (1) of this Article, the company's creditors may claim them, and the company may demand that each partner or shareholder - even if he is bona fide - return what he received from them.
A partner or shareholder shall not be required to return the profits distributed to him in accordance with the provisions of paragraph (1) of this Article, even if the company suffers losses in subsequent periods.
Regulations shall specify the controls necessary to implement the provisions of this article.
All partners shall share profits and losses in proportion to their respective shares in the capital. If they agree to deprive any of them of profit or to exempt them from loss, this agreement shall be considered as if it were not there.
However, it is permissible to agree in the company's articles of incorporation to vary the proportions of the partners in profits and losses.
It may be agreed to exempt a partner who provides only his labor from contributing to the loss, provided that he has not been paid for his labor.
If the partner's share is limited to his work, and the company's articles of association do not specify his share in the profit or loss, his share shall be the same as the share of the lowest partner in the company's capital.
If, in addition to his labor, the partner provides a cash or in-kind share, he has a share in the profit or loss for his labor share and another share for his cash or in-kind share.
The ownership of the shares in the Solidarity Company, the Simple Partnership Company and the Limited Liability Company shall be transferred by registration in the Commercial Register, and the transfer of ownership of the share shall not be considered in the face of the company or third parties except from the date of such registration.
The shares of the unlisted shareholding company and the simplified shareholding company shall be traded by registration in the shareholders' register stipulated in Article (118) of the Law, and the transfer of ownership of the share shall not be considered in the face of the company or third parties except from the date of such registration.
The shares of the listed shareholding company are traded on the capital market in accordance with the provisions of the Capital Market Law and its executive regulations.
A company director or board member must adhere to the duties of care and loyalty, in particular the following:
Exercise its duties within the limits of the powers assigned to it.
B- Working for the benefit of the company and promoting its success.
C. Make or vote on decisions independently.
D. Exercise reasonable and foreseeable care, attention, diligence, and skill.
Avoiding conflicts of interest.
F. Disclose any direct or indirect interest in the works and contracts carried out on behalf of the company.
G. Not to accept any benefit granted to him from third parties in relation to his role in the company.
The regulations shall specify the provisions of this article.
Neither the director of the company, nor a member of its Board of Directors, may have any direct or indirect interest in the works and contracts carried out on behalf of the company, except with the authorization of the partners, the General Assembly, the shareholders, or those who authorize him.
Neither the director of the company, nor a member of its board of directors, may participate in any business that would compete with the company or compete with the company in any branch of the activity it is engaged in, except with the authorization of the partners, the General Assembly, the shareholders, or those who authorize him.
Neither a director of the company, nor a member of its board of directors, may exploit the company's assets, information, or investment opportunities presented to him as a director or a member of its board of directors or presented to the company for his direct or indirect benefit.
The regulations shall specify the controls necessary to implement the provisions of paragraphs (1), (2) and (3) of this Article.
Paragraph (1) of this Article shall not apply to the following:
Works and contracts made pursuant to public competition.
Businesses and contracts that aim to fulfill personal needs if they are carried out under the same terms and conditions that the company follows with the general customers and contractors and are within the company's usual activity.
Any other works or contracts specified by the regulations in a manner that does not conflict with the company's interest.
In the event that its director or board member violates paragraph (1) of this Article, the Company shall have the right to claim before the competent judicial authority to annul the contract and oblige him to pay any profit or benefit realized by him therefrom.
If its director or board member violates paragraph (2) of this article, the company shall be entitled to claim before the competent judicial authority for appropriate compensation.
The director and members of the Board of Directors shall be jointly liable to compensate the company, partners, shareholders or third parties for damage arising from the violation of the provisions of the Law, the Company's Memorandum of Association or Articles of Association, or from their errors, negligence or default in the performance of their duties.
Any condition to the contrary is as if it were not there.
Liability shall be either personal for an individual director or member, or joint for all directors or all members of the Board of Directors if the decision is issued unanimously, and if the decision is issued by a majority of opinions, dissenting directors or members shall not be held liable if they expressly state their objection in the minutes of the meeting. Absence from the meeting at which the decision is issued shall not be considered a reason for exemption from liability unless it is proven that the absent director or member was unaware of the decision or was unable to object to it after being informed of it.
The company shall provide insurance coverage for its director or board member during his/her term of office or membership against any liability or claim arising from his/her capacity.
The company may file a liability suit against the director or members of the board of directors for violating the provisions of the law, the company's memorandum of association or articles of association, or for their errors, negligence or failure to perform their duties, resulting in damage to the company, and the partners, general assembly or shareholders shall decide to file this suit and appoint someone to represent the company in its prosecution, and if the company is in liquidation, the liquidator shall file the suit.
If any liquidation proceedings are initiated against the Company in accordance with the Bankruptcy Law, such suit shall be filed by its legal representative.
One or more partners or shareholders representing five percent of the company's capital, unless the company's memorandum of association or articles of association stipulate a lower percentage, may file a suit for the company's liability if the company fails to file it, provided that the main objective of filing the suit is to achieve the company's interest, that the suit is based on a valid basis, and that the plaintiff is bona fide and a partner or shareholder in the company at the time of filing the suit.
In order to file the lawsuit referred to in paragraph (2) of this Article, the director of the company or members of its board of directors, as the case may be, must be informed of the intention to file the lawsuit at least fourteen days prior to the date of filing the lawsuit.
A partner or shareholder may file a personal lawsuit against the director or members of the board of directors if the mistake made by them would cause him special damage.
The approval of the partners, general assembly or shareholders, as the case may be, to discharge the director or the members of the board of directors shall not prevent the filing of lawsuits in accordance with Article (29) of the Law.
Except in the cases of forgery and fraud, a suit for liability shall not be heard after five years from the end of the fiscal year of the company in which the harmful act occurred or three years from the termination of the employment of the director or membership of the board of directors concerned, whichever is later.
A company director or board member shall be deemed to have performed his or her duty in the decision he or she made or voted on in good faith, if
If he has no interest in the subject matter of the decision.
If he has familiarized himself with the subject matter of the decision to the extent appropriate in the surrounding circumstances and according to his reasonable belief.
C- If he firmly and rationally believes that the decision is in the best interests of the company.
The burden is on the plaintiff to prove otherwise.
For the purposes of this Article, a resolution means acting or not acting on a matter relating to the Company's business.
The competent judicial authority may, at the request of the partner or shareholder, charge the company the expenses it incurs to file a liability lawsuit, regardless of its outcome, if he files the lawsuit in good faith, and it is in the company's interest to file such lawsuit.
The personal creditor of the partner or shareholder may request the competent judicial authority to receive his right from the share of the debtor partner or shareholder in the net profits distributed.
If the company is dissolved, the creditor's right transfers to the debtor's share of the company's assets after paying its debts.
Subject to the provisions of the Movable Property Security Law and other relevant laws, the personal creditor of a partner or shareholder, in addition to the right referred to in Article (33) of the Law, may request the competent judicial authority to:
a. Sell the necessary shares of that partner to receive his right from the proceeds of their sale, and the remaining partners shall have the right to recover those shares in accordance with the provisions of the Law.
b. Selling as many of that shareholder's shares as necessary to receive his right from the proceeds of their sale.
The shareholders - in the unlisted shareholding company and the simplified shareholding company - shall have the priority to purchase these shares within (fifteen) days from the date they are offered for sale if the company's articles of association stipulate so.
Solidarity company: A company established by two or more natural or legal persons who are personally and jointly liable for the company's debts and obligations, in which the partner acquires the status of a merchant.
The articles of association of a solidarity company must include the following information
a. The names of the partners, and their details; b. Company name; c. The company's headquarters.
D- The purpose of the company. E- The capital of the company and its distribution to the partners, and an adequate definition of the share that each partner has pledged to provide and its due date. F- The duration of the company, if any. G- The management of the company. H- The decisions of the partners and the quorum required for their issuance. I- How profits and losses are distributed among the partners. J- The start and end date of the fiscal year. K- Termination of the company. L- Any other terms, conditions or statements that the partners agree to include in the company's articles of incorporation and do not conflict with the provisions of the law.
The solidarity company is managed by its partners, and the legal entity determines its representative in the management.
The partners may agree in the company's articles of incorporation or in a separate contract to appoint one or more directors.
If there are multiple directors, whether partners or non-partners, without specifying the competence of each of them and without stipulating that none of them may be solely responsible for management, each of them may independently perform any act of management, and the other directors may object to any act before it is binding against third parties, in which case the majority of the directors' opinions shall prevail, and if the opinions are equal, the matter must be submitted to the partners for a decision in accordance with Article (38) of the Law.
The director - or the directors if there are more than one - shall perform all acts of management that fall within the purpose of the company, and represent it before the judiciary, arbitration bodies and third parties, unless the company's memorandum of association expressly stipulates that his powers are restricted.
In all cases, the company shall be bound by every act performed by the director in its name and within the limits of its purpose, unless the person with whom he dealt is in bad faith.
Decisions of the partners shall be issued by a numerical majority; unless the decision relates to amending the company's memorandum of association, it must be issued by the unanimity of the partners, unless otherwise stipulated in the memorandum of association.
The director is prohibited from engaging in activities that exceed the purpose of the company except by a decision of the partners or an explicit provision in the company's articles of incorporation.
This prohibition applies in particular to the following actions:
a. Establishment or closure of branches. b. Donations, except for the usual small donations. c. Guaranteeing the company to third parties. d. Reconciliation of the company's rights. e. Selling or mortgaging the company's real estate (unless the sale is within the company's purpose). f. Selling or mortgaging the company's commercial shop (store). g. Borrowing on behalf of the company.
A partner may not - without the consent of the other partners - practice for himself or for others an activity of the type of the company's activity, nor may he be a partner, director or board member in a company that competes with it or an owner of shares or shares representing an influential percentage in another company practicing the same activity. If the partner violates this, the company may request the competent judicial authority to consider the actions he performed for his own account as having been carried out on behalf of the company, and, in addition, the company may demand compensation from him.
